<paragraph blockId="2.[151,760,1182,2071]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,331,1182,1205]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Molecular data.</emphasis>
<collectionCode box="[337,383,1182,1205]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">BIN</collectionCode>
<collectionCode box="[390,467,1182,1205]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">BOLD</collectionCode>
: 
<collectionCode box="[474,530,1182,1205]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">ABA</collectionCode>
0482 (n = 2, 2 public, 1 from Altai); 
<collectionCode box="[307,353,1214,1237]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">BIN</collectionCode>
<collectionCode box="[360,437,1214,1237]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">BOLD</collectionCode>
: AAD3659 (n = 9, 9 public, 0 from Altai). The distance of the cluster with the specimens from the Altai and 
<collectingCountry box="[354,481,1278,1301]" name="Switzerland" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
(
<collectionCode box="[496,574,1278,1301]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">BOLD</collectionCode>
: 
<collectionCode box="[582,639,1278,1301]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">ABA</collectionCode>
0482) from the second one with north European specimens is 3.41%. That is the reason why 
<collectionCode box="[403,476,1342,1365]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">BOLD</collectionCode>
automatically created two BINs. However, we did not find any noticeable differences in habitus and genitalia compared with European specimens. Therefore we classify all specimens as one species where the maximum intraspecific divergence of the barcode region reaches 3.56%.
</paragraph>
